								<a class="commentlink" href="#comment-99286" title="">Friday, 25 April 2014</a>
							</div>
						<p>I have this theory that a lot of this notion of being "nice" to people revolves around the general human desire to avoid confrontation. I spent several years in upper management at a listed company (eugh, I know), and I was accused on more than one occasion of enjoying confrontation merely because I told someone (in front of other staff members) that they were incompetent.</p>
<p>I belong(ed) very much to the "praise in private, criticise in public" school of performance communication thought. Why? Public praise is rarely done for the good of the person being praised. More often than not it is done to make the person heaping the praise seem like a kind and benevolent person. Praise in private makes the person feel far more valued, as the praise is genuine and not part of a weekly-board-meeting-speech.</p>
<p>Public criticism (the act of "calling someone out", so to speak) is great. The person being criticised (and I have been on the receiving end of that many, many times) develops a thick skin, a useful attribute, and also has the benefit of defending their position (which is a very different thing from explaining and/or justifying a mistake). Public criticism, when it is done in a way that attacks the problem and not merely the person, is a way of forcing change from generally stubborn, thinking humans. It is the bane of the stupid to sit in a corner and cry because their boss/friend/random-person-on-the-Internet was mean to them instead of letting it elicit change.</p>
<p>In the end before I left to go start my own thing I was loved by many of my staff, loathed by some. I had a string of grievances that had been filed against me with HR (I averaged 2 a month at one point), but some of those who had filed even several grievances against me had changed and become a better developer/sysadmin/project manager/whatever precisely because I had not couched their incompetence in nice words or gentle sarcasm. Being "nice" has its place, it is up to the discerning man to figure out what that place is.</p>
						</li>

										<li id="comment-99288" class="commentbody"><div class="commenthead"><img alt='chett`s avatar' src='http://trilema.com/default_avatar.png' class='avatar avatar-32 photo' height='32' width='32' />								<div class="commentcount">2</div>
